  abstract = {\textbackslash{}textlessp\textbackslash{}textgreater Quantification of fine-scale movement, performance, and energetics of hunting by large carnivores is critical for understanding the physiological underpinnings of trophic interactions. This is particularly challenging for wide-ranging terrestrial canid and felid predators, which can each affect ecosystem structure through distinct hunting modes. To compare free-ranging pursuit and escape performance from group-hunting and solitary predators in unprecedented detail, we calibrated and deployed accelerometer-GPS collars during predator-prey chase sequences using packs of hound dogs ( \textbackslash{}textlessitalic\textbackslash{}textgreaterCanis lupus familiaris\textbackslash{}textless/italic\textbackslash{}textgreater , 26 kg, \textbackslash{}textlessitalic\textbackslash{}textgreatern\textbackslash{}textless/italic\textbackslash{}textgreater = 4\textendash{}5 per chase) pursuing simultaneously instrumented solitary pumas ( \textbackslash{}textlessitalic\textbackslash{}textgreaterPuma concolor\textbackslash{}textless/italic\textbackslash{}textgreater , 60 kg, \textbackslash{}textlessitalic\textbackslash{}textgreatern\textbackslash{}textless/italic\textbackslash{}textgreater = 2). We then reconstructed chase paths, speed and turning angle profiles, and energy demands for hounds and pumas to examine performance and physiological constraints associated with cursorial and cryptic hunting modes, respectively. Interaction dynamics revealed how pumas successfully utilized terrain (e.g., fleeing up steep, wooded hillsides) as well as evasive maneuvers (e.g., jumping into trees, running in figure-8 patterns) to increase their escape distance from the overall faster hounds (avg. 2.3\texttimes{} faster). These adaptive strategies were essential to evasion in light of the mean 1.6\texttimes{} higher mass-specific energetic costs of the chase for pumas compared to hounds (mean: 0.76 \textbackslash{}textlessitalic\textbackslash{}textgreatervs.\textbackslash{}textless/italic\textbackslash{}textgreater 1.29 kJ kg \textbackslash{}textlesssup\textbackslash{}textgreater-1\textbackslash{}textless/sup\textbackslash{}textgreater min \textbackslash{}textlesssup\textbackslash{}textgreater-1\textbackslash{}textless/sup\textbackslash{}textgreater , respectively). On an instantaneous basis, escapes were more costly for pumas, requiring exercise at {$\geq$}90\% of predicted \$\textbackslash{}backslashdot \{\textbackslash{}backslashmathrm\{V \}\}\{\textbackslash{}backslashmathrm\{O\}\}\_\{2\textbackslash{}backslashmathrm\{MAX\}\}\$ and consuming as much energy per minute as approximately 5 min of active hunting. Our results demonstrate the marked investment of energy for evasion by a large, solitary carnivore and the advantage of dynamic maneuvers to postpone being overtaken by group-hunting canids. \textbackslash{}textless/p\textbackslash{}textgreater},
